Aggrieved supporters of the All Progressives Congress (APC) in Bayelsa State yesterday dismissed as mere ‘academic exercise’ the decision of the party to file a case at the Supreme Court for a review of the February 13, 2020 ruling nullifying the mandate of Chief David Lyon over the anomaly discovered in the certificates of his running mate, Senator Degi Eremienyo. The group, under the aegis of the Progressive Youths for Progress and Accountable Development (PYPAD), said although the party has the right to seek for a review, the proper review should have been done during the party’s selection process in order to discover the irregularities in the educational documents of Eremienyo. The group,  in a statement issued yesterday and signed by its Coordinator Kelvin Olotu, stated that ‘as far as we are concerned, it’s just an academic exercise, for David Lyon, Sylva and the APC ‘’. ‘’If they say that they are appealing the judgment of the Supreme Court, are they going to claim that either the Supreme Court spelt his name in error or his names were spelt in error going by the names in public domain. Five different names on five different certificates and somebody in Nigeria will say, yes, he graduated from all these universities with different names and that he is qualified”. ‘’But this can only point to the fact that there will be a very bad judicial, or wrong judicial precedent that anybody can go and use any dead man’s certificate and claim that he’s the owner of that certificate”. On the protest by some sponsored youths to the private residence of Justice Mary Odili, the group condemned the action and described it as a shameless show of desperation by the top chieftains of the party. According to the group, ‘’Secondly, for them to show themselves shamelessly going to protest all over places destroying people’s properties after which because Slyva and Oshiomole are living on the same street with Justice Mary Odili, they went further to protest in Justice Mary Odili’s house making it too personal and all point to one fact”.